Under a law revised earlier in March to cover the coronavirus, the prime minister can declare a state of emergency if the disease poses a “grave danger” to lives and if its rapid spread threatens serious economic damage. The virus has already increased Japan’s recession risk. If a state of emergency is declared, governors in hard-hit regions would have to take steps such as asking people to stay home, closing schools and other public facilities and cancelling large events. (Reporting by Linda Sieg Editing by Shri Navaratnam) Please note you must be a Maverick Insider to comment. Sign up here or sign in if you are already an Insider.